data.content:
MSTest has `CollectionAssert` and specific assert methods that give **much better failure messages** than `Assert.IsTrue`. Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Count checks
    Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count);
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // All items match a condition
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Item exists in collection
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` | Failure shows actual count |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Failure shows "Expected 3, got 5" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clearer intent and message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(condition)` | Add a **message parameter** | Otherwise failure just says "expected True, got False" |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**

```csharp
// Verify exact contents (order-independent)
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);

// Verify exact contents + order
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);

// Check membership
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, specificUser);

// All items are of a type
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User));

// No nulls
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

// No duplicates
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);
```

The general rule: **avoid `Assert.IsTrue`** for anything that has a dedicated assert method — you'll get far more useful failure messages.
